":"1337","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1453":"1453","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bailiffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for an officer of a court of justice, from Middle English <i>bailli</i>, <i>baillif</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>bailli(s)</i>, <i>baillif</i>). The term could denote the king's officer in a county, hundred, town, castle, or forest, or an elected town officer, a magistrate, an officer of a court, serving warrants and enforcing judgments. In Middle English, a bailiff often denoted the agent of a lord in managing a manor, collecting rents, etc., but in the early modern period the term gradually because specialized as denoting an officer of justice under a sheriff, who executes writs and processes, distraints, and arrests. Compare the variant   Bayliff  ,   Bayliss   and also   Bailey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bayliff","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailiff  . See also   Bayliss  ."]},{"name":"Bayliss","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailiff  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>, an occupational name for an officer of a court of justice, whose duties included serving writs, distraining goods, and (formerly) arresting people. In England it was formerly a status name for the chief officer of a hundred (administrative subdivision of a county). The derivation is from Middle English, Old French <i>bailis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i> (adjective), ‘pertaining to an attendant or porter’ (see   Bailey  ).","History: Thomas Baylies, a prominent Quaker, came to Boston from London in 1737."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":4,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLeve